POC 0 Rig — Terraform Build Plan (for Claude Code)


What this is. A build plan for a self-contained Azure rig that proves the
POC 0 mechanism from Cloud Port: a stateless Container App performing an
LDAPS simple bind against a domain controller across a simulated hybrid
boundary. It is built in a personal / free-tier Azure account as portable
Terraform, so the corporate version is later a tfvars swap.

What it proves: the LDAPS-bind auth mechanism, cross-boundary DNS, the NSG
path, and the Terraform/IaC itself.
What it does NOT prove (separate tenant, simulated transport): corporate RBAC,
corporate Azure Policy, and reachability to the real ALTOP-DC01 over the real
link. Keep that line in any writeup so the green check stays honest.

Audience: Claude Code. Build in the numbered chunks below, in order. Each chunk
is independently terraform apply-able and ends in an acceptance check — do
not start the next chunk until the current check passes. Pause for human review at
each chunk boundary.




Ground rules (apply to every chunk)


Parameterize everything environment-specific — subscription ID, tenant ID,
region, resource-group names, address spaces, tags, domain name, bind-account DN,
base DN, name prefix. Zero hardcoded IDs or names inside modules. The corporate
port must be a different terraform.tfvars, nothing else.
Globally-unique names (storage account, ACR, Key Vault, any public-DNS name)
derive from a name_prefix variable — never hardcode them.
Remote state in an Azure Storage backend, not local terraform.tfstate.
(Chunk 0 stands this up.)
Pin the providers (azurerm, plus random/tls as needed) to explicit
versions. Register resource providers explicitly — a fresh subscription has
many unregistered (Microsoft.App, Microsoft.ContainerRegistry,
Microsoft.OperationalInsights, Microsoft.Network, Microsoft.Compute).
Cost discipline (free-tier budget): small B-series VMs; a budget/cost
alert at ~$5 in Chunk 0; no VPN Gateway (peering replaces it); no Azure
Bastion (use JIT or a locked-down jump path); deallocate the DC VM between
sessions. Default everything to the smallest viable SKU.
Never domain-join the Container App. The app does an LDAPS bind over a TLS
socket — nothing more. Domain-join fights the stateless/scale-to-zero design and is
not needed.
Suggested layout: a root config that calls modules/network, modules/dc,
modules/app, with scripts/ for DC bootstrap and validate/ for the bind test.
Add one module per chunk so each chunk is a clean increment.



Resource groups & naming (cross-cutting — decide up front)

Resource groups — split by lifecycle, and make creation optional.


For the rig, create three RGs mirroring the boundary you're simulating: a
networking/shared RG (both VNets, peering, private DNS, NSGs — long-lived); an
on-prem-sim RG (the Samba DC VM, its disk, the jump path — the one you deallocate
/ rebuild); and a cloud-app RG (Container Apps env, ACR, Log Analytics — under
active iteration). Splitting by lifecycle lets you destroy and rebuild the app side,
or stop the DC side, without disturbing the wired network — and keeps cost legible per
area.
Names come from name_prefix (e.g. rg-<prefix>-net, -onprem, -app);
modules receive the RG name + location, they never invent their own.
Make RG creation a flag (e.g. create_resource_groups): each RG switches between
azurerm_resource_group (create — your rig) and a data source (reference an existing
one — corporate). In corporate you'll be handed RGs scoped to you with Contributor
and usually no right to create new ones; if the Terraform hardcodes "I own the RG,"
the corporate apply fails on the first resource. This flag is the single most
important porting affordance.


Naming — decide the shape now so it ports as values, not edits.


Keep name_prefix short (a few chars). Several resources are globally unique
across all of Azure with tight charsets: storage account (3–24, lowercase
alphanumeric, no hyphens), ACR (5–50, alphanumeric), Key Vault (3–24,
alphanumeric + hyphens). Derive these as ${prefix}${suffix} with a random suffix so
re-applies and the corporate apply both get a valid, unique name.
Derive every name from variables/locals — never hardcode — so corporate's naming
standard (often CAF-style <type>-<workload>-<env>-<region>) is a tfvars change, not a
sweep through modules. Expect corporate to mandate their convention via Policy;
off-pattern names may be denied at apply.
The realm/domain name is a naming decision with teeth. Pick a distinct test
realm (e.g. a subdomain of a domain you own, or a clearly-test *.lab) — don't
mirror the real corporate domain. The realm + DC hostname produce the DC FQDN,
which is exactly what the LDAPS cert SAN must match and what the app connects by,
and the realm drives the base DN. Keep realm, DC hostname, base DN, and
bind-account DN all as variables — the corporate swap changes these strings and nothing
else. (Avoid bare .local where you can; it's common in labs but invites mDNS/resolver
quirks.)
Tag everything from the start (owner, purpose=poc0, env, a teardown/expiry
reminder). Corporate requires tags via Policy, and on a personal account a
"delete-after" tag is a useful nudge against a forgotten running VM.



Chunk 0 — Terraform foundation & guardrails

Goal: a working Terraform skeleton with remote state, pinned providers, the
variable surface, and a cost alarm — before any rig resources exist.

Build:


backend.tf — azurerm remote state (a storage account + container; this can be
bootstrapped once by hand or via a tiny separate config, then referenced).
providers.tf — azurerm pinned; features {}; explicit
azurerm_resource_provider_registration (or document az provider register) for
Microsoft.App, Microsoft.ContainerRegistry, Microsoft.OperationalInsights,
Microsoft.Network, Microsoft.Compute.
variables.tf + terraform.tfvars.example — at minimum: name_prefix,
location, tags, subscription_id, tenant_id, the three RG names +
create_resource_groups flag (see Resource groups & naming), plus address-space and
realm/domain placeholders the later chunks fill in.
A budget (azurerm_consumption_budget_subscription) with an alert at a low
dollar threshold and your email.


Acceptance check: terraform init succeeds against the remote backend;
terraform plan is clean; the budget alert is visible in the portal; no rig
resources created yet.

Gotchas: the state storage account name is globally unique — derive from
name_prefix. Provider registration can take a few minutes; let it finish before
Chunk 1.


Chunk 1 — Two VNets + peering + private DNS (the simulated boundary)

Goal: recreate production's shape — a cloud network and an on-prem network
joined by a link — using two VNets and peering (peering stands in for the hybrid
VPN/ExpressRoute, since both sides are already in Azure).

Build (modules/network):


Resource group(s) — the networking/shared RG here, the on-prem-sim and
cloud-app RGs as their resources land (per Resource groups & naming; honor the
create_resource_groups flag — create vs. reference).
Cloud VNet with an app subnet sized for a VNet-integrated Container Apps
environment (Consumption-only env wants a dedicated subnet — size per the current
Container Apps requirement, e.g. a /23; confirm the minimum at build time and
parameterize the prefix).
On-prem VNet with a dc subnet and a small mgmt/jump subnet.
Non-overlapping address spaces between the two VNets (and chosen so they won't
collide with likely corporate ranges later — parameterize).
Bidirectional VNet peering between cloud and on-prem VNets.
A private DNS zone for the AD domain name, linked to both VNets. (Actual
name resolution comes online once the DC is up in Chunk 3; set the VNet DNS
server to the DC's reserved static IP here or in Chunk 2.)


Acceptance check: both peering links report Connected; the private DNS zone
exists and is linked to both VNets; address spaces don't overlap.

Gotchas: decide the DC's static IP now and reserve it, so the VNet DNS-server
setting can point at it before the DC exists. Don't put anything in the app subnet yet
if it's delegated to Container Apps — delegation can block other resources.


Chunk 2 — The DC VM (bare) + admin access

Goal: a Linux VM positioned to become a Samba-AD domain controller —
provisioned and reachable, but not yet provisioned as a DC.

Build (modules/dc, part 1):


Linux VM (small B-series, e.g. B2s; an LTS Ubuntu/Debian image) in the
dc subnet, with a static private IP (the one reserved in Chunk 1).
No public IP.
A data disk with host caching = None, mounted at /var/lib/samba —
the directory database and SYSVOL live here, off the OS disk and well off the
ephemeral temp disk.
NSG on the dc subnet: deny-by-default; allow management (SSH) only from
the jump path; the bind port (636) from the app subnet is opened in a later chunk.
Admin access without Bastion: Azure JIT VM access, or a tiny jump VM with
a public IP restricted by NSG to your home IP. Pick the cheaper one and parameterize
it; default to JIT if available. Use SSH keys, not passwords.
Set the VNet DNS server to the DC's static IP (if not already done in Chunk 1).


Acceptance check: the VM boots; reachable over the chosen admin path via SSH; the
data disk is mounted at /var/lib/samba with caching None; no public IP on the DC.

Gotchas: keep it B-series and plan to deallocate between sessions (stopping
halts compute billing; you keep paying only cheap disk). A Linux DC tolerates
stop/start far better than Windows, but AD/Kerberos still cares about time —
install chrony/ntp so the clock stays sane across restarts.


Chunk 3 — Provision the Samba-AD domain + test identities

Goal: stand up the AD domain on Samba and the identities the bind test needs. No
promotion-reboot dance — a Linux DC provisions in a single pass.

Build (scripts/dc-setup.sh via cloud-init / custom-data or a custom-script
extension):


Install Samba (the AD-DC packages) + chrony. Disable any stub resolver that
occupies port 53 (e.g. systemd-resolved's listener) so Samba's internal DNS can
bind it; point the host's own resolver at 127.0.0.1.
Provision the domain as an AD DC:
samba-tool domain provision --server-role=dc --use-rfc2307 --dns-backend=SAMBA_INTERNAL --realm=<REALM> --domain=<DOMAIN> (realm/domain from
variables, e.g. CORP.EXAMPLE.LOCAL / CORP). Enable and start the samba service.
Create an OU, two test users (known passwords from sensitive variables —
test-only, never real), and a bind service account (samba-tool user create /
ou create). A plain user can read userAccountControl, so the bind account needs no
special rights.
Confirm the samba AD DC service is serving DNS for the realm.


Acceptance check: the domain is up (samba-tool domain info / samba-tool user list from SSH); the realm resolves from both VNets (test resolution from a probe in
the cloud VNet); the bind service account exists.

Gotchas: the port-53 / systemd-resolved conflict is the classic Samba-AD
provisioning failure — handle it in the bootstrap script. Keep test passwords in
sensitive variables / a git-ignored tfvars file. Provisioning is one pass, but if
the script can't complete before the VM finishes first boot, re-run it idempotently
rather than reprovisioning.


Chunk 4 — LDAPS on the DC

Goal: turn on LDAPS (636) with a trustworthy cert, and export the CA cert for the
client to trust.

Build (extends modules/dc / dc-setup.sh):


A Samba AD DC serves LDAPS on 636 by default using the TLS material in
/var/lib/samba/private/tls/ (cert.pem, key.pem, ca.pem). For the rig, issue
your own CA + DC cert (a small tls-provider step in Terraform, or openssl) and
point smb.conf at them: tls enabled = yes, tls keyfile, tls certfile,
tls cafile.
Ensure the DC cert's SAN matches the FQDN the app will connect by (the DC's realm
FQDN). This is the single most common LDAPS failure.
Export the CA cert (PEM) as a Terraform output / artifact for Chunk 5 to bake
into the container's trust store.


Acceptance check: an LDAPS bind over 636 with TLS succeeds locally —
openssl s_client -connect <dc-fqdn>:636 shows the cert/chain, and
ldapsearch -H ldaps://<dc-fqdn> -D <bind-dn> -w <pw> -b <base-dn> returns a user from
the jump box; the exported CA cert is available to the next chunk. Test a
wrong/expired cert path too so you know what failure looks like.

Gotchas: the cert's SAN must match the connect FQDN and the client must trust
the issuer — these are the two LDAPS failure modes, and they're identical against
corporate's real DC (whose cert chains to their internal CA). Solving CA-trust once
here is representative, not throwaway. (Samba's auto-generated self-signed cert works
for a quick smoke test, but issue your own so you control the SAN and CA.)


Chunk 5 — The Container App that performs the bind

Goal: a stateless, non-domain-joined, scale-to-zero Container App that binds to
the DC across the peering — the actual POC 0 proof.

Build (modules/app + validate/):


A Log Analytics workspace + a VNet-integrated Container Apps environment in
the cloud VNet / app subnet (VNet integration is required so egress routes over the
peering to the DC).
ACR (or use a public base image) holding a tiny LDAP-bind test app (e.g.
Python + ldap3): given a username/password it attempts an LDAPS simple bind and
returns success/failure; a second endpoint does a service-account bind then reads
userAccountControl (to show disabled/expired/locked detection — a plain bind
validates the password but not account policy).
The app carries the CA cert from Chunk 4 in its trust store and points its TLS
config at it. Config via env/secrets: DC FQDN, base DN, bind-account DN.
Scale-to-zero (min replicas 0) — it sits in the Container Apps free grant.
Not domain-joined. No SMB, no Kerberos/NTLM machinery — just the TLS bind.


Acceptance check (the POC 0 matrix):


Valid user + correct password → bind succeeds.
Valid user + wrong password → bind fails (cleanly, distinguishable).
The app resolves the DC by name across the boundary (DNS working), not just by
IP. (If name resolution misbehaves first time, connecting by IP isolates DNS from
the bind; then fix DNS so the name path works — corporate will require by-name.)
(Optional) service-account bind reads userAccountControl for a disabled test user.


Gotchas: Container Apps respects the VNet's DNS settings when VNet-integrated;
verify name resolution explicitly. The bind connects by the FQDN that matches the
cert SAN — mismatches here are the usual failure. Keep the app stateless; this is the
shape the real cloud login will take.


Chunk 6 — Harden, validate, and document teardown

Goal: tighten the boundary, run the full validation, and capture cost/teardown
hygiene.

Build / do:


NSG hardening: app subnet → DC allowed only on 636; management/SSH locked to
the jump path / home IP; default-deny elsewhere. This mirrors the real invariant —
the cloud reaches in over a narrow path; on-prem initiates nothing toward the cloud.
Run and record the validation matrix from Chunk 5.
Write the teardown/cost note: deallocate the DC between sessions; the budget
alert from Chunk 0 is live; nothing carries real secrets or data; the rig is empty
infrastructure only.
Produce a short "proven vs pending" statement for the POC 0 writeup: mechanism
(LDAPS bind, cert trust, cross-boundary DNS, IaC) proven against a Samba-AD
stand-in DC; pending validation against the real Windows ALTOP-DC01 and
corporate RBAC/policy over the real link. (Samba-AD is a faithful stand-in for the
bind itself; the Windows-AD-specific surface — cert auto-enrollment, schema/attribute
and GPO nuances — is the slightly larger "pending" gap to keep honest.)


Acceptance check: validation matrix passes; NSGs are least-privilege; budget alert
confirmed; teardown steps documented.


Porting to corporate (what changes — and what doesn't)

When the rig is proven, the corporate version should be a different tfvars plus
two structural swaps, not a rewrite:


tfvars swaps: subscription/tenant IDs, region, RG names, address spaces, tags,
name_prefix, domain_name, base DN, bind-account DN, and the CA trust
(corporate's internal CA instead of your rig CA).
Structural swaps: the peering (rig) becomes the real hybrid link
(VPN/ExpressRoute, owned by corporate networking); your Samba-AD stand-in DC
becomes the real Windows ALTOP-DC01 (you create no DC — you point at theirs).
The bind code, cert-trust handling, DNS path, and NSG rules are unchanged by the
swap.
Declare the RBAC you need as explicit resources (role assignments, managed
identities, Key Vault access policies) so the corporate apply surfaces exactly
which grants are missing — treat the rig as producing a manifest of required
permissions, since in your own account you're Owner and will never hit the wall
corporate will put up.


Cost summary (free-tier sanity)

Free/near-free: the two VNets, peering, private DNS, NSGs, and the scale-to-zero
Container App (monthly free grant). Real (small) cost: the DC VM — a small
Linux B-series running Samba-AD (no Windows license, so cheaper than a Windows
DC), deallocated between sessions. Avoid: VPN Gateway, Azure
Bastion left running, and any second always-on VM (defer the SMB-share VM
entirely — the cloud never touches \\mars directly, so it's not part of POC 0). The
whole rig fits inside the $200 / 30-day window with room to spare; the day-one budget
alert is the backstop.